The '''Yangtze River''' ({{IPAc-en|lang|pron|ˈ|j|æ|ŋ|t|s|i}} or {{IPAc-en|ˈ|j|ɑː|ŋ|t|s|i}}), known in China as the '''Chang&nbsp;Jiang''', is the longest [[rivers of Asia|river]] in [[Asia]] and the [[List of rivers by length|third-longest]] in the world.  It flows for {{Convert|6418|km|mi|0|sp=us}} from the glaciers on the [[Qinghai-Tibet Plateau]] in [[Qinghai]] eastward across [[Southwest China|southwest]], [[South Central China|central]] and [[East China|eastern China]] before emptying into the [[East China Sea]] at [[Shanghai]].  It is also [[List of rivers by discharge|one of the biggest rivers by discharge volume in the world]]. The Yangtze drains one-fifth of the land area of the [[People's Republic of China]] (PRC) and its river basin is home to one-third of the [[Demographics of the People's Republic of China|PRC's population]].<ref>[http://www.cjw.gov.cn/index/river/liuyugk-3.asp?link=1]. Accessed 10 Sept 2010. {{zh-icon}}</ref>

Along with the [[Yellow River]], the Yangtze is the most important river in the [[history of China|history]], [[culture of China|culture]] and [[Economy of China|economy]] of China.  The prosperous [[Yangtze River Delta]] generates as much as 20% of the [[Historical GDP of the People's Republic of China|PRC's GDP]]. The Yangtze River flows through a wide array of ecosystems and is itself habitat to several [[Endemism|endemic]] and endangered species including the [[Chinese alligator]] and the [[Yangtze sturgeon]].  For thousands of years, people have used the river for water, irrigation, sanitation, transportation, industry, boundary-marking and war.  The [[Three Gorges Dam]] on the Yangtze River is the [[List of the largest hydroelectric power stations|largest hydro-electric power station in the world]].<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/IOTD/view.php?id=38879
|title=Three Gorges Dam, China : Image of the Day
|publisher=earthobservatory.nasa.gov
|accessdate=2009-11-03
}}
</ref><ref>[http://internationalrivers.org/node/356 International Rivers, Three Gorges Dam profile], Accessed August 3, 2009</ref>

In recent years, the river has suffered from industrial pollution, agricultural run-off, [[siltation]], and loss of wetland and lakes, which exacerbates seasonal flooding.  Some sections of the river are now protected as [[Protected areas of China|nature reserves]].  A stretch of the Yangtze flowing through deep gorges in western [[Yunnan]] is part of the [[Three Parallel Rivers of Yunnan Protected Areas]], a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]].

==Names==

===Chinese===
{{anchor|Chinese name|Chinese names}}
Early Chinese literature calls the Yangtze River simply {{lang|zh|'''江'''}} ([[Old Chinese]]:&nbsp;''*kˤroŋ''<ref name=baxjiang>Baxter, Wm. H. & Sagart, Laurent. ''{{PDFlink|1=[http://crlao.ehess.fr/docannexe.php?id=1207 Baxter–Sagart Old Chinese Reconstruction]|2=1.93&nbsp;MB}}'', p. 56. 2011. Accessed 12 August 2013.</ref>), a character that came to mean ''any'' river by the [[Han Dynasty]]. The [[Chinese character|character]] is a [[phono-semantic compound]], combining {{lang|zh|氵}} ("water") with the former homophone {{lang|zh|工}} (today ''gōng'', but pronounced ''*kˤoŋ'' in Old Chinese<ref>Baxter & al. (2011), {{PDFlink|1=[http://crlao.ehess.fr/docannexe.php?id=1207 p. 69]|2=1.93&nbsp;MB}}.</ref>). This ''Krong'' was probably a word taken from an [[Austroasiatic]]-speaking people in the area such as the [[Baiyue|Yue]], owing to its similarity to [[Proto-Vietnamese]] ''*krong'', [[Mon language|Mon]] ''krung'', and other cognates, all meaning "river".<ref>Philipsen, Philip. ''Sound Business: The Reality of Chinese Characters'', [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qyPndWdUrdIC&pg=RA1-PT12 p. 12]. iUniverse (Lincoln), 2005. Accessed 12 August 2013.</ref> The epithet {{lang|zh|長}} (or the simplified  {{lang|zh|长}}), which means "long", was first formally applied to the river during the [[Six Dynasties]] period.{{citation needed|date=August 2013}}

[[History of geography|Modern geography]] traces the Yangtze to its source, but traditionally the Chang Jiang proper was considered to begin at the confluence of the [[Jinsha River|Jinsha]] and [[Min River (Sichuan)|Min]] [[rivers in China|rivers]] in southern Sichuan or to follow the ''Min'', which was previously thought to be the main course.<ref name=eb1911/><ref name=kincha/> Above this, its major tributaries had &ndash; and locally still have &ndash; other names:
*The [[Ulan Moron]] ({{lang|zh|沱沱河}}, <small>[[pinyin|p]]</small>&nbsp;''Tuótuó Hé'', <small>lit.</small>&nbsp;"Tearful River"<ref>Powers, John & al. ''Historical Dictionary of Tibet'', [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=LVlyX6iSDEQC&pg=PT155 p. 155]. Scarecrow Press (Plymouth), 2012. Accessed 14 August 2013.</ref>{{refn|But note Mei Zuyan who claims the Chinese name merely [[transliteration into Chinese|transliterates]] a former Tibetan name.<ref>{{lang|zh|梅祖彦}} [Mei Zuyan]. {{lang|zh|《晚年随笔》}} ["Old Age Essays"], [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pxBQtx3BBMoC&pg=PA289 p. 289]. "The Changjiang Sanxia Hydro Power Development". 1997. Accessed 13 August 2013. {{en-icon}}</ref>}}) is the officially-recognized source of the Yangtze, running from the [[Geladandong]] glaciers to a confluence with the Dam Chu. ''Ulaan Mörön'' is [[Mongolian language|Mongolian]] for "Red River".
*The [[Dangqu River]] ({{lang|zh|当曲}}, <small>[[pinyin|p]]</small>&nbsp;''Dāngqū'') is the actual geographic headwater of the Yangtze. It derives its name from the [[Classical Tibetan|Tibetan]] for "Marsh River" ({{lang|bo|འདམ་ཆུ}}, <small>[[Wylie transliteration|w]]</small>&nbsp;''<nowiki>'</nowiki>Dam Chu'').
*The [[Tongtian River]] ({{lang|zh|通天河}}, <small>lit.</small>&nbsp;"River Passing Through Heaven") runs {{convert|813|km|abbr=on|sp=us}} from the confluence of the Dam Chu and Tuotuo to [[Yushu Tibetan Autonomous Prefecture|Yushu]], where it is joined by the [[Batang River|Batang]]. This section was previously known as the Murui-ussu (<small>lit.</small>&nbsp;"Winding Stream") in Mongolian<ref>Ravenstein, Ernest & al. (ed.). ''The Earth and Its Inhabitants'', Vol. VII: "East Asia: Chinese Empire, Corea, and Japan", [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jCxPAAAAYAAJ&q=%22murui+ussu%22 p. 199]. D. Appleton & Co. (New York), 1884. Accessed 14 August 2013.</ref> and sometimes confused with the nearby [[Baishui River|Baishui]].<ref name=kincha>[[Yule, Henry]]. ''The River of Golden Sand: The Narrative of a Journey Through China and Eastern Tibet to Burmah'', Vol. 1, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Uuk2OQeMwsMC&pg=PA35 p. 35]. "Introductory Essay". 1880. Reprint: Cambridge Univ. Press, 2010. Accessed 14 August 2013.</ref>
*The [[Jinsha River]] ({{lang|zh|金沙江}}, <small>lit.</small>&nbsp;"Gold Dust"<ref name=archie>Little, Archibald. ''The Far East'', [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=kxNxhSy1BZUC&pg=PA63 p. 63]. 1905. Reprint: Cambridge Univ. Press (Cambridge), 2010. Accessed 13 August 2013.</ref> or "Golden-Sanded River"<ref name=jon/>) runs {{convert|2308|km|abbr=on|sp=us}} from the confluence of the Tongtian and Batang near Yushu to [[Yibin]], where it is joined by the [[Min River (Sichuan)|Min]].

Below Yibin, particular stretches of the Yangtze sometimes acquired local or poetic names: the "[[Sichuan River]]" ({{lang|zh|川江}}, <small>[[pinyin|p]]</small>&nbsp;''Chuānjiāng''), named for the adjacent [[provinces of the PRC|province]], is sometimes used to describe the river between Yibin and [[Yichang]]; the "Jing River" ({{lang|zh|荆江}}, <small>[[pinyin|p]]</small>&nbsp;''Jīngjiāng''), named for the [[Jingzhou (ancient China)|region]] and [[Jingzhou|city]] of Jingzhou, is sometimes given to the next stretch beside [[Hubei]] and [[Hunan]]; and the "Yangzi River" (<small>[[traditional characters|t]]</small>&nbsp;{{lang|zh|揚子江}}, <small>[[simplified character|s]]</small>&nbsp;{{lang|zh|扬子江}}, <small>[[pinyin|p]]</small>&nbsp;''Yángzǐjiāng''), named for the [[Yangzhou (ancient China)|region]] and [[Yangzhou|city]] of Yangzhou,{{refn|Probably by way of its former ferry crossing ({{lang|zh|揚子}} or {{lang|zh|揚子津}}, <small>[[pinyin|p]]</small>&nbsp;''Yángzǐ'' or ''Yángzǐjīn'').<ref>{{lang|zh|安民}} [An Min]. [http://www.yznews.com.cn/yzwb/html/2010-01/23/content_92703.htm {{lang|zh|《夜晤扬子津》}}] ["Yangtze Ferry"]. 23 January 2010. {{zh-icon}}</ref><ref>{{lang|zh|百度百科}} [Baidu Baike]. {{lang|zh|《扬子江》}} ["Yangtze River"]. Accessed 13 August 2013. {{zh-icon}}</ref>}} was poetically given<ref>E.g., in 文天祥 <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Wen Tianxiang]]<nowiki>]</nowiki>. [http://zhidao.baidu.com/question/76255314.html {{lang|zh|《揚子江》}}] ["Yangzi River"]. 1276. Accessed 13 August 2013. {{zh-icon}}</ref> to the river just inland from its mouth near present-day [[Shanghai]]. (Despite its former popularity among the peoples of the lower Yangtze,<ref name=eb1911>Jamieson, George. ''Encyclopædia Britannica'', 11th ed. "[http://www.1911encyclopedia.org/Yangtsze-Kiang Yangtsze-Kiang]". Cambridge Univ. Press, 1911. Accessed 14 August 2013.</ref> who spread it to most European languages, ''Yangzijiang'' today is very uncommon within China itself and is typically understood {{ndash}} if at all {{ndash}} as a foreign misnomer.) Among the river's other informal names in Chinese are {{lang|zh|大江}} (''Dàjiāng'', the "Big River") and {{lang|zh|黄金水道}} (''Huángjīn Shuǐdào'', the "Golden Waterway"), although it shares the latter with the [[Grand Canal of China|Grand Canal]].<ref>{{lang|zh|百度百科}} [Baidu Baike]. [http://baike.baidu.com/view/403279.htm {{lang|zh|《黄金水道》}}] ["Golden Waterway"]. Accessed 13 August 2013. {{zh-icon}}</ref>

===English===
{{anchor|English name|English names}}
The river was called '''Quian''' ({{lang|zh|江}}) and '''Quiansui''' ({{lang|zh|江水}}) by [[Marco Polo]]<ref>Pelliot, Paul. ''Notes on Marco Polo'', Vol. 2, [http://dsr.nii.ac.jp/toyobunko/III-2-F-c-104/V-2/page/0222.html.en p. 818]. L'Académie des Inscriptions e Belles-Lettres e avec le Concours du Centre national de la Recherche scientifique (Paris), 1959&ndash;1973. Accessed 13 August 2013. {{en-icon}}</ref> and appeared on the earliest English maps as '''Kian''' or '''Kiam''',<ref name=moll>E.g., Moll, Herman. "[http://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/detail/RUMSEY~8~1~3744~430080:The-Empire-of-China-and-island-of-J The Empire of China and island of Japan, agreeable to modern history.]" Bowles & Bowles (London), 1736. Accessed 13 August 2013.</ref><ref>''Encyclopædia Britannica'', 3rd ed. "[http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=tIFMAAAAMAAJ&q=kiam#search_anchor Kiam]". Bell & Macfarquhar (Edinburgh), 1797. Accessed 14 August 2013.</ref> all recording [[Chinese dialects|dialects]] which preserved forms of the [[Middle Chinese]] pronunciation of {{lang|zh|江}} as ''Kæwng''.<ref name=baxjiang/> By the mid-19th century, these romanizations had standardized as '''Kiang'''; ''Dajiang'', e.g., was rendered as "Ta-Kiang". "Keeang-Koo",<ref name=bell>Bell, James. ''A System of Geography, Popular and Scientific; or a Physical, Political, and Statistical Account of the World and its Various Divisions'', Vol. V, Part I, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QVURAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA215 p. 215]. "Chinese Tartary". A. Fullarton & Co. (London), 1849. Accessed 13 August 2013.</ref> "Kyang Kew",<ref name=tan>Tanner, B. "[http://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/detail/RUMSEY~8~1~239031~5512191:China-divided-into-it-s-Great-Provi China dividided into it's<!--sic--> Great Provinces According to the best Authorities]". Mathew Carey (Philadelphia), 1795. Accessed 13 August 2013.</ref> "Kian-ku",<ref name=repo>Bridgman, Elijah (ed.) ''[[The Chinese Repository]]'', Vol. I, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=h0YPAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA37 pp. 37 ff]. "Review. ''Ta Tsing Wan-neën Yih-tung King-wei Yu-too'',&ndash;'A General Geographical Map, with Degrees of Latitude and Longitude, of the Empire of the Ta Tsing Dynasty&ndash;May It Last Forever', by Le Mingche Tsinglae". Canton Mission Press (Guangdong), 1833.</ref> and related names derived from mistaking the Chinese term for the mouth of the Yangtze ({{lang|zh|江口}}, <small>[[pinyin|p]]</small>&nbsp;''Jiāngkǒu'') as the name of the river itself.

[[File:Portrait map of China.jpg|thumb|left|A map of China depicting the Yellow River's southerly path following its stabilization by the Grand Eunuch [[Li Xing]]'s public works after the [[1494 Yellow River flood|1494 flood]].]]
The name '''Blue River''' began to be applied in the 18th century,<ref name=moll/> apparently owing to a former name of the Dam Chu{{refn|[[Mongolian language|Mongolian]]:&nbsp;{{lang|mon|Xөх Мөрөн}}, ''Höh'' or ''Kök Mörön''.<ref>Konstam, Angus. ''Yangtze River Gunboats 1900&ndash;49'', [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uVZrlJzKPlQC&pg=PT17 p. 17]. Osprey Publishing (Oxford), 2012. Accessed 13 August 2013.</ref>}} or Min{{refn|Recorded as bearing the local Chinese name of {{lang|zh|清水}} (''Qīngshuǐ''), literally meaning "Clear Water[way]".<ref>Davenport, Arthur. ''Report upon the Trading Capabilities of the Country Traversed by the Yunnan Mission'', [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=K-BAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA10 pp. 10 ff]. Harrison & Sons (London), 1877.</ref>}} and to analogy with the [[Yellow River]],<ref>Aloian, Molly. ''Rivers Around the World: The Yangtze: China's Majestic River'', [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Tmw-00JaCtMC&pg=PA6 p. 6]. Crabtree Publishing Co. (New York), 2010. Accessed 13 August 2013.</ref><ref>Room, Adrian. ''Placenames of the World'', [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=PzIer-wYbnQC&pg=PA395 p. 395]. 1997. Reprint: McFarland (Jefferson, N.C.), 2003. Accessed 13 August 2013.<!--NB: his direct translation of Yangzi's characters is spurious.--></ref> but it was frequently explained in early English references as a 'translation' of ''Jiang'',<ref>''The Modern Part of an<!--sic--> Universal History, from the Earliest Accounts to the Present Time'', Vol. XXXVII, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MisIAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA57 p. 57]. "Of the Empires of China and Japan". (London), 1783.</ref><ref>Wilkes, John. ''Encyclopaedia Londinensis, or, Universal Dictionary of Arts, Sciences, and Literature,'' Vol. XI, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mFcMAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA851 p. 851]. "Koko Nor". J. Adlard (London), 1812.</ref> ''Jiangkou'',<ref name=bell/> or ''Yangzijiang''.<ref>Liber, Nadine. ''Life''. "A Scary Pageant in Peking", [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8kUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA60 p. 60]. 4 September 1964. Accessed 14 August 2013.</ref> Very common in 18th- and 19th-century sources, the name fell out of favor due to growing awareness of its lack of ''any'' connection to the river's Chinese names<ref name=jon>Davis, John. ''The Chinese: A General Description of the Empire of China and Its Inhabitants'', Vol. 1, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=A6RNeE46WtUC&pg=PA132 pp. 132 ff]. C. Knight, 1836.</ref><ref name=StJ>''The St. James's Magazine'', Vol. XIV, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sEIxAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA230 p. 230]. "A Cruise on the Yangtze Kyang". W. Kent & Co. (London), 1865.</ref> and to the irony of its application to such a muddy waterway.<ref name=StJ/><ref>Moncrieff, A.R.H. ''The World of To-day: A Survey of the Lands and Peoples of The Globe as Seen in Travel and Commerce'', Vol. I, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BvVaAAAAQAAJ&q=%22Blue+River%22,+%22its+stream+is+as+turbid%22 p. 42]. Gresham Publishing Co. (London), 1907.</ref>

The 1615 [[De Christiana expeditione apud Sinas|Latin account]] of the [[Jesuit missions to China]] included descriptions of the "Iansu" and "Iansuchian".<ref name=chrex>[[Ricci, Matteo]] & al. ''De Christiana Expeditione apud Sinas Suscepta ab Societate Jesu'', IV,  [http://books.google.com.au/books?id=iLsWAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA365 pp. 365 ff]. 1615. Reprint: B. Gualterus (Cologne), 1617. Accessed 14 August 2013. {{la-icon}}</ref> The posthumous account's translation of the name as "Son of the Ocean"<ref name=chrex/><ref>Ricci, Matteo & al. Samuel Purchas (trans.) in ''Hakluytus Posthumus, or Purchas His Pilgrimes'', Vol. XII, [http://archive.org/stream/hakluytusposthu14purcgoog/hakluytusposthu14purcgoog_djvu.txt p. 305]. "A Generall Collection and Historicall representation of the Jesuites entrance into Japon and China, untill their admission in the Royall Citie of Nanquin". 1625. Reprint: MacLehose & Co. (Glasgow), 1906. Accessed 14 August 2013.</ref> shows that [[Matteo Ricci|Ricci]], who by the end of his life was fluent in literary Chinese, was introduced to it as the homophonic {{lang|zh|洋子江}} rather than the 'proper' {{lang|zh|揚子江}}. Further, although [[History of rail transport in China|railroads]] and the [[Shanghai concessions]] subsequently turned it into a backwater, [[Yangzhou]] was the lower river's principal port for much of the [[Qing Dynasty]], directing [[viceroy of Liangjiang|Liangjiang]]'s important [[Economic history of China before 1912|salt monopoly]] and connecting the Yangtze with the [[Grand Canal of China|Grand Canal]] to [[Beijing]]. (That connection also made it one of the [[Yellow River|''Yellow'' River]]'s principal ports between the floods of [[1344 Yellow River flood|1344]] and the 1850s, during which time the Yellow River ran well south of [[Shandong peninsula|Shandong]] and discharged into the ocean only a few hundred miles away from the mouth of the Yangtze.<ref name=jon/><ref name=repo/>) By 1800, English cartographers such as [[Aaron Arrowsmith]] had adopted the French style of the name<ref>E.g., in Didier, Robert & al. "[http://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/detail/RUMSEY~8~1~3983~490062:L-Empire-de-la-Chine,-Dresse-d-apre? L'Empire de la Chine]". Boudet (Paris), 1751. Accessed 14 August 2013.</ref> as '''Yang-tse''' or '''Yang-tse&nbsp;Kiang'''.<ref>[[Arrowsmith, Aaron]]. "[http://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/detail/RUMSEY~8~1~233054~5509637:Asia--To-Major-James-Rennell,-Esq-r Asia]". G. Allen (London), 1801. Accessed 14 August 2013.</ref> The British diplomat [[Thomas Francis Wade|Thomas Wade]] emended this to '''Yang-tzu Chiang''' as part of his formerly popular [[Wade-Giles|romanization of Chinese]], based on the [[Beijing dialect]] instead of Nanjing's and first published in 1867. The spellings '''Yangtze''' and '''Yangtze&nbsp;Kiang''' was a compromise between the two methods adopted at the 1906 Imperial Postal Conference in Shanghai, which established [[Chinese Postal Map Romanization|Postal Map Romanization]]. [[Hanyu Pinyin]] was adopted by the PRC's [[1st National People's Congress|First Congress]] in 1958, but it was not widely employed in English outside of mainland China prior to the normalization of diplomatic relations between the United States and the PRC in 1979; since that time, the spelling '''Yangzi''' has also been used.

===Tibetan===
{{anchor|Tibetan name|Tibetan names}}
The source and upper reaches of the Yangtze are located in [[Tibetan people|ethnic Tibetan]] areas of [[Qinghai]].<ref>Yang & al. ''Tibetan Geography'', p. 73. China Intercontinental Press, 2004. ISBN 7-5085-0665-0.</ref> In [[Tibetan languages|Tibetan]], the Tuotuo headwaters are the ''Marchu'' ({{lang|bo|མར་ཆུ་}}, <small>[[Wylie transliteration|w]]</small>&nbsp;''Mar Chu'', <small>lit.</small>&nbsp;"Red River"). The Tongtian is the ''Drichu'' ({{lang|bo|འབྲི་ཆུ་}}, <small>[[Wylie transliteration|w]]</small>&nbsp;''<nowiki>'</nowiki>Bri Chu'', <small>lit.</small>&nbsp;"River of the Female [[Yak]]"; [[transliteration into Chinese|transliterated]] into Chinese as {{lang|zh|直曲}}, <small>[[pinyin|p]]</small>&nbsp;''Zhíqū'').

==Geography==
[[Image:Map of the Yangtze River.gif|thumb|320px||Yangtze watershed]]
[[File:TroyParfitt2.JPG|thumb|right|Cruise on the Yangtze River before sunset]]
The river originates from several tributaries, two of which have claims to be the source.  The PRC  government has recognized{{when|date=July 2013}} the source of the Tuotuo tributary at the base of a glacier lying on the west of [[Geladandong]] Mountain in the [[Tanggula Mountains|Dangla Mountain Range]] on the eastern part of the [[Qinghai-Tibet Plateau]]. However, the geographical source (i.e., longest river distance from the sea) lies in wetlands at {{coord|32|36|14|N|94|30|44|E}} and {{convert|5170|m|abbr=on|sp=us}} above sea level at the head of the Dan Qu tributary.<ref>Wong How Man (2005) [http://www.cers.org.hk/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&id=27&layout=blog&Itemid=61 New and longer Yangtze source discovered.]</ref> These tributaries join and the river then runs eastward through [[Qinghai]] (Tsinghai), turning southward down a deep valley at the border of [[Sichuan]] (Szechwan) and [[Tibet Autonomous Region|Tibet]] to reach [[Yunnan]]. In the course of this valley, the river's elevation drops from above {{convert|5000|m|abbr=on|sp=us}} to less than {{convert|1000|m|abbr=on|sp=us}}. The headwaters of the Yangtze are situated at an elevation of about {{convert|4900|m|abbr=on|sp=us}}. In its descent to sea level, the river falls to an altitude of {{convert|305|m|abbr=on|sp=us}} at Yibin, Sichuan, the head of navigation for riverboats, and to {{convert|192|m|abbr=on|sp=us}} at Chongqing (Chungking). Between Chongqing and Yichang (I-ch'ang), at an altitude of {{convert|40|m|abbr=on|sp=us}} and a distance of about {{convert|320|km|abbr=on|sp=us}}, it passes through the spectacular Yangtze Gorges, which are noted for their natural beauty but are dangerous to shipping.

It enters the basin of Sichuan at [[Yibin]]. While in the Sichuan basin, it receives several mighty tributaries, increasing its water volume significantly. It then cuts through [[Mount Wushan]] bordering [[Chongqing]] and [[Hubei]] to create the famous [[Three Gorges]]. Eastward of the Three Gorges, [[Yichang]] is the first city on the Yangtze Plain.

After entering Hubei, the Yangtze receives more water from thousands of lakes.{{weasel-inline|date=July 2013}} The largest of these lakes is [[Dongting Lake]], which is located on the border of [[Hunan]] and Hubei provinces, and is the outlet for most of the rivers in Hunan. At [[Wuhan]], it receives its biggest tributary, the [[Han River (Hanshui)|Han River]], bringing water from its northern basin as far as [[Shaanxi]].

At the northern tip of Jiangxi, [[Lake Poyang]], the biggest freshwater lake in China, merges into the river. The river then runs through [[Anhui]] and [[Jiangsu]] provinces, receiving more water from innumerable smaller lakes and rivers, and finally reaches the [[East China Sea]] at [[Shanghai]].

Four of China's five main freshwater lakes contribute their waters to the Yangtze River. Traditionally, the upstream part of the Yangtze River refers to the section from Yibin to Yichang; the middle part refers to the section from Yichang to [[Hukou County]], where [[Lake Poyang]] meets the river; the downstream part is from Hukou to Shanghai. It is home to many thousands of people.{{weasel-inline|date=July 2013}}

The origin of the Yangtze River is dated to about 45 million years ago in the [[Eocene]],<ref>Richardson N.J.,Densmore A.L.,Seward D.  Wipf M. Yong L. (2010). Did incision of the Three Gorges begin in the Eocene?  Geology  38: 551-554. {{doi|10.1130/G30527.1}}</ref> but many people{{who|date=July 2013}} do not accept this point.<ref>Wang, JT; Li, CA; Yong, Y; Lei, S (2010) Detrital Zircon Geochronology and Provenance of Core Sediments in Zhoulao Town, Jianghan Plain, China. Journal of Earth Science  21 (3): 257-271.</ref>
<gallery caption= widths="221px" heights="150px" perrow="4">
Image:长江源头.jpg|The glaciers of the Tanggula Mountains, the source of the Yangtze River
image:Yangtze at First Bridge.jpg|The Tuotuo River, a headwater stream of the Yangtze River, known in Tibetan as Maqu, or the "Red River"
image:Cn1202-03.jpg|The first turn of the Yangtze at Shigu (石鼓) in [[Yunnan]] Province, where the river turns 180 degrees from south- to north-bound
File:Yangzi River - by Peter Morgan.jpg|The [[Jinsha River]] in Yunnan
